---
/**
 * Affiliate Disclosure Policy Page
 *
 * FTC-compliant disclosure page explaining our affiliate relationships.
 * This page is linked from affiliate disclosure notices throughout the site.
 *
 * @module pages/disclosure
 */

import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  meta={{
    title: "Affiliate Disclosure Policy | StackHunt",
    description: "Learn about our affiliate relationships, how we make money, and our commitment to editorial independence."
  }}
>
  <main class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none prose-headings:text-zinc-100 prose-p:text-zinc-400 prose-a:text-indigo-400 hover:prose-a:text-indigo-300 prose-strong:text-zinc-200 prose-li:text-zinc-400">
      <h1>Affiliate Disclosure Policy</h1>

      <p class="lead text-xl text-zinc-400">
        Transparency is important to us. This page explains how StackHunt earns revenue
        and how it affects (and doesn't affect) our content.
      </p>

      <h2>How We Earn Revenue</h2>

      <p>
        Some of the links on StackHunt are affiliate links. This means that if you click
        on a link and make a purchase or sign up for a service, we may receive a small
        commission from the company at <strong>no additional cost to you</strong>.
      </p>

      <p>
        These affiliate relationships help support our independent research and keep
        StackHunt free for everyone to use.
      </p>

      <h2>Our Editorial Independence</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Affiliate relationships never influence our research, analysis, scores, or recommendations.</strong>
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Research is automated and objective</strong> - Our AI research system doesn't know
          or care which tools have affiliate programs. It searches the same 12 queries for every tool.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Analysis is source-based</strong> - Scores and insights come from official documentation,
          professional reviews, and community discussions - not from affiliate potential.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Equal treatment</strong> - Tools without affiliate programs receive the same depth
          of research and analysis as those with programs.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Free alternatives promoted</strong> - We often recommend free and open-source
          alternatives that generate no revenue for us.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Transparent scoring</strong> - Our scores reflect features, user feedback, and
          contextual fit - factors determined before affiliate relationships are even considered.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Our revenue comes from users who find our recommendations helpful and choose to use our
        affiliate links. This aligns our incentives with providing accurate, helpful information
        rather than promoting expensive tools.
      </p>

      <h2>How We Label Affiliate Links</h2>

      <p>
        We strive to be transparent about affiliate links:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Pages containing affiliate links display a disclosure banner at the top</li>
        <li>Individual affiliate links may be labeled with "affiliate" or similar indicators</li>
        <li>"Visit Website" buttons on tool pages may be affiliate links</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>AI-Assisted Research</h2>

      <p>
        StackHunt uses AI to automate research and analysis at scale. Our process combines
        automated web research with human verification to ensure accuracy and trustworthiness.
      </p>

      <h3>How It Works</h3>

      <p>
        Our "Hunter" system performs comprehensive research on each tool:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Automated Research</strong> - We run 12 parallel Google searches to gather
          information from multiple sources: official websites, professional reviews (G2, Capterra,
          Gartner), technical documentation, and community discussions (Reddit, HackerNews).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>AI Analysis</strong> - Google's Gemini AI processes the search results in two passes:
          first to extract verifiable facts (pricing, features, platforms), then to synthesize
          contextual insights (who it's best for, common gotchas, tribal knowledge).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Source Attribution</strong> - Every claim is linked to its source URL and
          classified by source type (official, editorial, community) and claim type (fact vs opinion).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Human Verification</strong> - All AI-generated reviews are created as drafts
          and verified by our team before publishing. We correct errors and update outdated information.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        For complete details on our research methodology, see our
        <a href="/methodology" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">Methodology page</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Source Classification</h3>

      <p>
        We classify every source to help you assess credibility:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Official sources</strong> - The tool's own website, documentation, or announcements
          (highest authority for factual claims)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Editorial sources</strong> - Professional review sites (G2, Capterra) and tech
          publications (PCMag, TechRadar)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Community sources</strong> - Reddit discussions, HackerNews threads, user forums
          (valuable for real-world experiences but subjective)
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Fact vs Opinion</h3>

      <p>
        We clearly distinguish between verifiable facts and subjective opinions:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Facts</strong> - Objectively verifiable information like pricing tiers, platform
          availability, feature lists, and integration support
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Opinions</strong> - Subjective assessments like user experience quality, customer
          support ratings, and value judgments from community discussions
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Every pro and con in our reviews includes metadata showing the source URL, source type,
        and whether it's a fact or opinion.
      </p>

      <h2>Data Freshness & Accuracy</h2>

      <p>
        Software products change frequently - pricing updates, new features launch, companies
        get acquired. We take data freshness seriously:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Verification dates</strong> - Every tool page displays when the information
          was last verified, so you know how current the data is.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stale data warnings</strong> - If data hasn't been verified in over 60 days,
          we display a clear warning banner.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Community reporting</strong> - Users can report outdated information, which
          automatically queues the tool for re-research.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Automatic updates</strong> - Popular tools are periodically re-researched
          to ensure accuracy.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Report Inaccuracies</h2>

      <p>
        Found something wrong or outdated? We want to know. When you report an inaccuracy:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>Your report is reviewed by our team</li>
        <li>If confirmed, we queue the tool for immediate re-research</li>
        <li>The tool is re-analyzed using our full 12-query research process</li>
        <li>Updated information is published with a new verification date</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        We take accuracy seriously because our business depends on providing trustworthy
        recommendations.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="/corrections" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">
          Submit a correction request
        </a>
      </p>

      <h2>What We Don't Do</h2>

      <p>
        Transparency means being honest about our limitations:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't test tools hands-on</strong> - Our reviews are based on publicly
          available information, not direct usage. This lets us cover more tools, but means
          we can't provide first-hand experience insights.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't contact vendors</strong> - All information comes from public sources
          (websites, reviews, community discussions). We don't get briefings or special access.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't have vendor partnerships</strong> - Beyond standard affiliate programs,
          we don't have NDAs, sponsorships, or special relationships that could bias our coverage.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We can't guarantee 100% accuracy</strong> - Software changes rapidly and sources
          can be outdated or incorrect. We verify everything we can, but errors can slip through.
          That's why we make corrections easy to report.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Questions?</h2>

      <p>
        If you have questions about our affiliate relationships, research methodology, or
        editorial policies, we're happy to clarify. Transparency is core to what we do.
      </p>

      <hr class="my-8" />

      <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500">
        Last updated: {new Date().toLocaleDateString('en-US', { month: 'long', year: 'numeric' })}
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
